<h3>The end of an era</h3>
<p>
    Much like the Edo period of japan, good things always come to an end. <br />
    (I actually don't know if the edo period was properous or not) <br />
    Time passed and I did some upgrades, like a replacing the left microcontroller with a USB-C promicro, and making a better TRRS cable. <br />
</p>
<p>
    This keyboard, as <i>unfinished and imperfect</i> as it is, can be considered a <b>completed project</b>.
</p>
<p>
    It's current state is good enough to use at home, and take to a cafe when I'm out and about doing my computer stuff. 
</p>
<img src="/assets/images/crkbd/hw-corne1.png" alt="Image of a my current corne build, in all it's glory"> <br />
<p class="img_subtitle">
    If it's good enough for Australia, is good enough for me. <br />
</p>

<hr />
<h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
<h3>From the ashes, another era... emerges?</h3>
<p>
    There is always another project, or another keyboard to be built. <br />
    One of the things I noticed after giving my wife the last standard mechanical keyboard I had (The one on my gaming puter), is that a crkbd, is not very good for gaming. <br />
    The row stagger makes it really hard to use wasd, ctrl is on a wierd spot, and the most important part, you need to switch layers to access the number keys. <br />
    Specially since I have mouse-keys configured on my Lower layer, I can't even access asd when using the numbers. <br />
</p>
<p>
    So the plan is to design and build another split keyboard! <br />
    Here is what I have in mind: <br />
    An ortholinear keyboard with un-even split, that gives left hand access up to the M key (that would be two columns more than normal) <br />
</p>
<img src="/assets/images/kbs/wootec.png" alt="Drawn plans of a woteec keyboard"> <br />
<p class="img_subtitle">
    Now that's sketchy! <br />
</p>
<p>
    The main benefit of this design, is that the left side would be more compact than a 60%, which is what I was using before, and still have all the keys I need for my CSGO nade bindings. <br />
    It shall be called "woteec", short for "WOrst Typing Experience Ever Created", though I highly doubt it actually would be the worst, since alphabetic keyboards exist. <br />
</p>
<p>
    That's pretty much all I got to say about keyboards for now, thought there's some other projects in the works. <br />
    I think it's kind of funny how it all went full circle, started at a 75% and finished on one. But the corne has been a great companion for the last couple years, I learnt touch typing on it, and it got me to a modest typing speed of 90 WPM. <br />
    I know it's not the highest, and there's people on querty going at 300 WPM, but typing is so confortable for me, 10/10 would recommend.
</p>

